8.1 Relational Operators
There are some operators called relational operators in Java used to do comparisons between operands. 

bits => 0, 1

Examples: 
1. 7 == 7 V
2. 7 != 7 F
3. 7 > 9 F
4. 7 < 9 V
5. 5 >= 8 F

p = "5 > 8" False OR
q = "5 == 8" False 

6. 5 <= 8 True

p = "5 < 8" True OR
q = "5 == 8" False 


8.2 Truth tables

Adriana 15

p = "Adriana 15 es un hombre"? False
q = "Adriana 15 es mayor de edad" False
p && q = "Tienes que hacer el servicio militar" 
False && False ==> False

Orlando

p = "Si tiene INE"? False
q = "Si tiene Acta de nacimiento" False
p || q = "Si tiene INE o Acta de nacimiento puede hacer tramite"
False || False => False


NOT
p => !p => 
!p => p

 LOGICAL AND TABLE       LOGICAL OR TABLE

 p | q | p && q            p | q | p || q
 V | V |   V               V | V |    V
 V | F |   F               V | F |    V
 F | V |   F               V | V |    V
 F | F |   F               F | F |    F

8.3 Logical Operators
The Logical Operators in Java are: and, or and not. To use these logical operators, we can use the following symbols: &&(and), ||(or), and !(not).

Example. Determine if given a number is a valid score

int score = -1;
score >= 0 && score <= 10

p = "score >= 0" F
q = "score <= 10" T
F && T ==> F


num < 0 && num > 10
{
	sout("Calificacion no valida")
}


Likewise, the operators ||(or) and !(not) are used to perform similar conditions.

8.4 Boolean expressions
A condition always returns a boolean value.

Example. Determine if a number is bigger than other.
i = 10
i > 5 -> False

8.5 Conditional Statement

The syntax of an if condition is simple

if(condition){
	statement(s);
}

Example 1. 
int age = 18

if (age >= 18){
	System.out.println("Can vote")
}

8.6 Else statement
We can determine the behaviour of our program depending if the condition is true or false. To do that, we can use an if-else statement.

The syntax is similar

if(condition){
	true statement;
} else {
	false statement;
}

8.7 Nested if-else statement
We can have multiple if-else statements and will look like this.

weather = "solado"

if(condition){
	true statement;
} else if (condition) {
	true else if statement;
} else if (condition) {
	true else if statement;
} else if (condition) {
	true else if statement;
} else if (condition) {
	true else if statement;
} else {
	"Clima no valido por el momento"
}

Example 1. Determine if A is bigger than B or B is bigger than A

int a = 8;
int b = 7;

if(a > b) System.out.println("A is bigger")
else if (a == b) System.out.println("A is equal than B")
else System.out.println("B is bigger than A")

Exercise. Given three numbers, determine the biggest.
A = 8
B = 7
C = 10


And we can have as many as we want

8.8 Ternary operation
We can use a ternary operation to determine if a value is true or false.
The syntax is the following

condition ? true statement: false statement

Example.
int i = 10;

(i % 2 == 0 ? "Even" : "Odd")

(i % 2 == 0 ? true : false)


Exercises.
1. Given two numbers a and b, determine if a is smallest than b or not.

2. Given a number, determine if that number is even or not.

3. Given the age of a person, determine if is a teenager or not. (13 - 19)

4. Given the weather of a city, propose a recommendation to the user.
"Soleado" => Usar bloqueador
"Lluvioso" => Usa un impermeable
"Nublado" => Lleva un paraguas
"Nevando" => Usa una chamarra y un sueter

5. Determine if a number is divided by 3, by 5 or by both.
nums = 9, 10, 15, 7.












